Key Match Events: Cody Gakpo curled in a finish after Xavi Simons had scampered 60 yards beyond an overcommitted midfield
Romano Schmid's goal was not signposted but Austria finally made ground down the left through their winger Patrick Wimmer
Marcel Sabitzer played Grillitsch in at the byline; the resulting cross, stood up deliciously, was bulleted in by a diving Schmid
Wout Weghorst arrived to shake things up and almost immediately headed down for Memphis Depay, cushioning and finishing in one smooth movement, to equalise again
Pre-Game Insights: Ralf Rangnick’s players walked towards the Olympiastadion’s furthest corner to join their fans in a serenade of Hey Jude
Austria have to fancy their chances when they face the runners-up from Group F, almost certainly Turkey or Czech Republic, on Tuesday
Rangnick rotated extensively again, partly because of a surfeit of players on yellow cards and to keep pace with Austria’s high-intensity style of play
Post-Match Reflections: Austria have completed Group D as its improbable winners
Rangnick and his dynamos have completed a thrilling evening’s work and have completed Group D as its improbable winners
The knockout draw was turned on its head by events here and in Dortmund; it would take a brave onlooker, now, to rule Rangnick and his dynamos out of a lung-busting run to the latter stages
Miscellaneous Highlights: Austria have now scored inside the first 10 minutes in six of their past seven games: you have to keep pace with them from the off
The Netherlands were guilty of bursting into life sporadically and were woefully open at the back when examined in any detail
Bart Verbruggen, the Netherlands goalkeeper, can only look on after an own goal by Donyell Malen opens the scoring
Others: The match will essentially be a home game for Austria, who will be fresh on arrival, given that the tie will take place in Leipzig, a city with strong connections to the Red Bull project
